pull_request.title: usdt: path is optional when attaching to pid
pull_request.body:
This PR has two commits currently which could arguably split into separate PRs.

The first commit adds listing of `usdt` probes if `bpftrace -l` is also invoked with `-p`.

```
$ bpftrace -p 30000 -l 'usdt:*python*'
usdt:/opt/bin/python3.7:line
usdt:/opt/bin/python3.7:function__entry
usdt:/opt/bin/python3.7:function__return
usdt:/opt/bin/python3.7:import__find__load__start
usdt:/opt/bin/python3.7:import__find__load__done
usdt:/opt/bin/python3.7:gc__start
usdt:/opt/bin/python3.7:gc__done
```

The second commit allows for omitting the path when describing the usdt probes to instrument so long as a pid was specified for attaching. For example:

```
$ bpftrace -p 30000 -e 'usdt::function__entry { printf("hi: %s %s\n", str(arg0), str(arg1)); } usdt::function__return { printf("bye: %s %s\n", str(arg0), str(arg1)); }'
Attaching 2 probes...
hi: /test.py fn
bye: /test.py fn
hi: /test.py fn
bye: /test.py fn
```

The initial motivation for omitting the path was because I was attempting to instrument a path for a process that was running in a mount namespace (i.e. in a container) and was trying to circumvent the various `stat()`s that were happing.

Initially, I attempted to use `/proc/<pid>/root/<path>` but unfortunately that leads to `EIO` when attempting to write in the child `/proc/<pid>/mem`.

Also, it turns out that in the upstream `libbcc` there are still some outstanding issues relating to mount namespaces, though generally, it's well behaved.

Tests are still a TODO, though I am not sure necessarily the right way to manage the harness for testing against things in containers.

The following is from the commit message for further details.

When instrumenting a pid the path to the binary is optional since the probes can be determined by discovering the probes by attaching to the process.

Practically, the path is resolved and associated with the attach point during the semantic analyzer path, though the irbuilder must also attach to the process to resolve the arguments.

Remove GetProviderFromPath in favor of discovering the provider by attaching to the process, which is the more reliable method. The path only has a passing relationship to the provider as defined by stapsdt.

Upstream `bcc_usdt_new_frompid` has an issue when instrumenting a process that is in a mount namespace, so for now don't include the path when attaching to a pid.

Relatedly, the `stat()` that occurs in the semantic analyzer is removed since it isn't namespace aware.

pull_request.title: Add `hasValue()` property to InternalAggregation
pull_request.body:
This allows consumers of any `InternalAggregation` to easily determine if the agg "has a value".  This is needed because InternalAggs represent "empty" in different manners according to convention.  Some use `NaN`, `+/- Inf`, `0.0`, etc.

The `XContent` deals with all these nuances and converts them to `null`, but internal consumers of the objects are stuck decoding the conventions themselves.

By adding `hasValue()`, the conventions can be handled internally and a simple interface is given for anything using InternalAggs.

The definition of "having a value" varies depending on agg, but generally:
 - If it is a metric agg, the agg has collected at least one value
 - If it is a bucketing agg, at least one of the buckets had doc_count > 0
 - Pipeline aggs behavior is variable and depends on the particular agg. E.g. derivatives always have a value because they are only added to the agg response if a value can be calculated. In contrast, a cumulative_sum will emit 0 even if no values are collected, so hasValue() depends on if any of the buckets it processes have a value themselves.

### So big :(
This PR turned out quite large... we have a lot of aggs apparently. About half is just adding assertions to tests.  If it's too unmanageable I suppose I could add a concrete placeholder in `InternalAggregation` and then implement aggs in chunks?  Open to suggestions. 

Didn't realize it would turn out so large when I started :)

### Things not addressed in this PR
There are places where we can use the new `hasValue()` internally to deduplicate some code.  This PR was already large (albeit simple changes), so I think we can tidy those up in followup PRs.

This also doesn't introduce any sort of `hasValue()` in script contexts, so scripts are unable to determine if the values they are receiving are real values or just empty placeholders.  That can also be done in a followup.

Related to #34903 

/cc @costin

pull_request.title: Save client id and secret when using grive -a
pull_request.body:
If you wanted to give a different than the default client id and secret, you always had to give that on the commandline. Now it's saved in the .give file. If given on the commandline, it's now also only used when 'auth/-a' is given, in normal runs it's not anymore valid (and errors out).

This is a workaround for #236 so you simply add your own client id and secret to get the sync going again.

This partly reverts #160 because it removes the possibility to set the client id and secret on the command line during a normal (not `-a`)  run. I found that intuitive as the corresponding refresh token was saved to disc and so changing the id/secret (on the command line) was actually not possible as long as you do not change the refresh token. (That's at least my understanding here, cc: @cgltower, @kuschuermann)

issue.title: ESGST Button opens Profile page instead of ESGST settings
issue.body:
**Description**
Clicking the ESGST Button o top opens the Profile page (https://www.steamgifts.com/account/settings/profile) instead of ESGST settings with version 8.1.3 (Dev.8). Only when already on the Profile page a new page gets loaded with the ESGST settings on it.

**Steps to Reproduce**
1. Go to any page but the profile page (I didn't test is from ALL the pages, obvioulsy, but All, Wishlist, Group,... the main ones)
2. Click on "ESGST"

**Expected Behavior**
The ESGST settings pop up

**Screenshots**
This seems to be the new ESGST settings page (**which is also missing the search settings feature**).

![download](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/18130829/49393097-9845c400-f730-11e8-9c9f-8e66b36108fa.jpg)

**System (please complete the following information):**
- ESGST: 8.1.3 (Dev.8)
- Browser: current Chrome 64bit version

**Additional Context**
I assume the new settings page should open whenever the ESGST button is clicked - not only when on the profile page.

comment.body: ESGST 8.1.3 (no Dev) shows the settings page when clicking on the button, though the profile page shows up right before the settings page.

issue.title: Simplify obtaining the 'drive_id' of an Office 365 Shared Library
issue.body:
Currently there is a detailed process to obtain the 'drive_id' of the Shared Library to sync.

In debugging #248, an easier process was identified which could be easily implemented as a command to 'get' the 'drive_id' of a given site name. 

 Implement that process as a new command line switch.
